      <h2>Getting Started: Setting Up Your Account</h2>
      <p>Visit <a href="/tradequote/">TradeQuote Pro</a> and create an account. The onboarding wizard asks for your trade type, service area, and business details. This feeds into your default template and pricing database. The setup takes under 5 minutes.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Trade type selection:</strong> Roofing, siding, concrete, HVAC, electrical, plumbing, landscaping, or general contracting — each comes with pre-configured line items</li>
        <li><strong>Service area setup:</strong> Define your coverage zones so estimates auto-populate travel or mileage charges</li>
        <li><strong>Business branding:</strong> Upload your logo, set company colors, and configure your standard terms and conditions</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Step 1: Create an Estimate Template</h2>
      <p>Good estimating starts with repeatable templates. In TradeQuote Pro, go to the Templates section and click "Create New Template." You can start from scratch or duplicate an existing template. Build your template around the work type you estimate most often.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Add labor line items:</strong> Crew size × hours × hourly rate. The tool calculates subtotals automatically</li>
        <li><strong>Add material line items:</strong> Quantity × unit price. You can save standard material costs so you don't re-enter them</li>
        <li><strong>Set default markup:</strong> Overhead percentage (e.g., 15%) + profit margin (e.g., 20%) applied to subtotals</li>
        <li><strong>Add optional line items:</strong> Permits, dump fees, equipment rentals, travel — things that vary per job</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Save your template with a clear name like "Standard 3-Ton AC Installation" or "2,000 sqft Asphalt Shingle Roof." The more templates you build, the faster your estimating gets.</p>

      <h2>Step 2: Generate a Client Estimate</h2>
      <p>When a lead calls ready for a quote, open TradeQuote Pro and click "New Estimate." Enter the client's name, address, and contact info. Select your template — the entire line-item structure populates instantly. Adjust quantities or swap materials as needed.</p>
      <p>The tool recalculates everything in real time. Change the square footage from 1,500 to 2,000 and the line-item totals update, the subtotal updates, the overhead and margin update, and the final price updates — all instantly. No formulas to check, no errors to catch.</p>

      <h2>Step 3: Add Custom Notes and Scope</h2>
      <p>An estimate without scope of work is an invitation for scope creep. TradeQuote Pro has a dedicated notes section where you describe exactly what the price includes and excludes.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Scope summary:</strong> Two or three sentences describing the full scope (e.g., "Remove and replace 3-tab asphalt shingles including felt underlayment, drip edge, and ridge vent")</li>
        <li><strong>Exclusions:</strong> Clearly state what the quote does not cover (e.g., "Does not include skylights, chimney flashing, or gutter replacement")</li>
        <li><strong>Terms:</strong> Payment schedule, valid-until date, and warranty information</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Clear scope in writing reduces disputes and improves the client's confidence in your professionalism. It also makes your estimate harder to compare purely on price — you've defined the value.</p>

      <h2>Step 4: Send the Estimate</h2>
      <p>When the estimate is ready, click "Send." TradeQuote Pro generates a branded PDF and emails it to the client with a preview link. The client can view it on any device — phone, tablet, or desktop — without downloading software.</p>
      <p>The delivery includes a "View Estimate" button that opens a clean, mobile-friendly page with all line items, totals, and your terms. Clients can click "Accept" or "Request Changes" right from the page. This removes the back-and-forth of "did you get my email?" and gives you a clear record of every estimate's status.</p>

